Content:
Okay just so I'm on the same page here....

South America was inhabited for about the last ~15k years, and North America for a bit longer, so that seems timeline accurate. 

Australia is at least 65,000 years so they're a little shy on that. 

China is around accurate as well, from what I can tell. 

The middle east was at least 150,000 years ago from what I can see. 

Europe 45,000 years ago or so. 

So the only egregious date I can see is that homo sapiens seem to have appeared roughly 300,000 years ago (not 130,000 years ago), right? 

Asking honestly on this one. 

As for the "they wore a feather on their head so they're all the same culture" I'm not touching that one.
explanation: Likely critical or skeptical language.

Content:
Seems to me their argument is that the original natives of North and South America as a distinct genetic group left Africa 130,000 years ago and traveled as a distinct group through Asia, across the Bering land bridge, and down to the tip of South America by 13,000 years ago. 

As opposed to the idea that African humans left Africa 130,000 years ago, spread across Asia, adapting and differentiating genetically along the way, until reaching the America's ~20,000 years ago and reaching the tip of South America by 13,000 years ago.
explanation: Likely critical or skeptical language.

Content:
There is a racist branch of Afro-centrism - sometimes influenced by the Nation of Islam - that black people and white people are a different species and that black people are superior. 

Some will pseudoscience biological evolution to claim that black Africans are the original human species and that other humans are less perfect mutations away from the original perfection. 

There is also the thing Afro-centrist historical revisionism that black Africans are basically behind all or most of the world's cultures, that Eqyptian monarchs such as Ramses and Nefertiti were black African (not just the Nubian dynasty), that the Americas were settled by black Africans, and so on.

Content: This is based on the black colonization myth. It's a black supremacist argument that states that black people or people of Sub-Saharan African descent colonized much of the world and became Native Americans. It implies that native peoples, among others, aren't the original inhabitants of the Americas, nor the original peoples of Asia, but blacks were the ones who colonized everything and they were killed in a massive genocide by native groups and whites. Content: Anthropologist here! The meme is pushing a pseudoscientific idea called hyperdiffusionism (the same ‚ÄúAncient Origins‚Äù nonsense that Graham Hancock peddles). The idea is that there was an ancient, superior, technologically advanced progenitor race that spread the knowledge of pyramid building, civilization, and apparently wearing feathers (ü§¶üèº‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è) across the globe before the Last Glacial Maximum. Or after it. Or during it. (Choose whichever you like, it‚Äôs all bollocks). The original hyperdiffusionist notion was that Atlanteans were the ancient global super-race, which Hancock enthusiastically pushed but now distances himself from because he‚Äôs afraid people won‚Äôt take him seriously (lol). Other hyperdiffusionism greatest hits include Lemurians, Ancient Aliens, and Black Olmecs, among others; they all stem from the racist notion that Black and brown peoples couldn‚Äôt have figured out how to build pyramids, cut straight lines into stones, move heavy things, etc without outside help.
